AB  - In this article, we present a Mach 15 air flow over a blunt wedge obtained with the direct molecular simulation (DMS) method. The resulting air mixture around the wedge contains N2, O2, NO, N, and O in their ground electronic states only. The wall is isothermal, with full momentum and energy accommodation. All PESs used to model the various air molecules interactions are from first-principles quantum mechanical calculations, with the exception of N2+NO and O2+NO interactions, which required surrogate semi-empirical surfaces. Via comparisons with computational fluid dynamics (CFD) predictions for this near-continuum, high-enthalpy flow, we show that the DMS solution can provide a stringent test case to enhance the fidelity of thermochemical and transport models utilized in continuum computations, at a level of detail beyond what is possible with experimentation. Notably, a significant difference in heat flux predictions is found here between the CFD and DMS methods, where the CFD is shown to under-predict wall heating due to a lower adiabatic wall temperature.
