TI  - Quantum counterfactuals based on weak measurement and interaction-free measurement
LA  - chi
JF  - Kexue Tongbao/chinese Science Bulletin
VL  - 68
IS  - 27
SP  - 3573
EP  - 3581
PY  - 2023
SN  - 20959419, 0023074x
PB  - Chinese Academy of Sciences
DO  - 10.1360/TB-2023-0418
AB  - Many counterfactual predictions are made by quantum theory, such as quantum tunneling and violations of Bell’s inequalities. Experimental verifications of these predictions demonstrate that quantum theory is reliable for the microscopic world. Despite its widespread application, consistent theoretical interpretations of quantum theory remain a challenge. Recently, Aharonov et al. proposed several new and intriguing counterfactuals based on quantum weak measurement and interaction-free measurement, such as the quantum violation of the pigeonhole principle and the departure of physical properties from particles, also known as the quantum Cheshire cat effect. These counterfactuals garnered considerable interest. Although no common consensus has been reached, many pioneering experiments have already been conducted in light of these theoretical proposals. Furthermore, these counterfactuals and the key concepts underlying them, weak measurement and interaction-free measurement, open up a whole new way of thinking about and understanding the strange quantum theory. Herein, our aim is to provide a unified perspective on these counterfactuals. The theoretical ideas, particularly the fundamental quantum concepts underlying these counterfactuals, are the focus of our attention. First, we present concise and insightful introductions to weak measurement and interaction-free measurement, which are the two key fundamental constructions for discussing all of the following quantum counterfactuals. Next, we discuss the quantum violation of the pigeonhole principle in depth, explicitly demonstrating that the key idea leading to the violation is destructive quantum interference between the possible paths of two particles traveling along the same path. Then, two key proposals of the quantum Cheshire cat effect are examined based on weak values of certain physical properties. Both proposals are built around interaction-free measurement, and the departure of physical properties from their bodies is realized based on the quantum Zeno effect. After introducing the weak measurement and weak value, the non-locality in the quantum Cheshire cat effect can be dismissed, and the physical properties leave the body continuously with infinitesimal quantum amplitudes. Meanwhile, during the departure, the total property in the entire space remains invariant. Finally, we present our conclusion on quantum counterfactuals, arguing that when coherent processes are endowed with concrete physical properties, counterfactuals are unavoidable. Throughout our discussions, we try to elaborate on the key roles played by the quantum concepts, quantum amplitudes, and quantum coherence in these counterfactuals. The idea behind weak measurement and weak value is that information about a coherent process can be obtained with sufficiently weak coupling. In other words, a quantum coherent process becomes observable with a weak measurement and even acquires a specific property quantified by a weak value. When compared to our conventional understanding of quantum coherent processes, this is a mind-boggling viewpoint. The idea behind interaction-free measurement is that weak amplitudes can cause large system evolution even if they cannot transport the body of the system, which is also astonishing! This demonstrates the enormous power of infinitesimal quantum amplitudes in quantum communication and computation. Therefore, all quantum counterfactuals provide new perspectives to further investigate these fundamental quantum concepts.
ER  -

