TI  - Non-Hertz-Millis scaling of the antiferromagnetic quantum critical metal
  via scalable Hybrid Monte Carlo
LA  - eng
JF  - Arxiv (cornell University)
PY  - 2022
PB  - Cornell University
AB  - We numerically study the $\mathrm{O}(3)$ spin-fermion model, a minimal model of the onset of antiferromagnetic spin-density wave order in a two-dimensional metal. We employ a Hybrid Monte Carlo (HMC) algorithm with a novel auto-tuning procedure, which allows us to study unprecedentedly large systems of $80 \times 80$ sites, even at criticality. To characterize the universality class of the quantum critical point, we extract the scaling exponents and functional form of the static and zero-momentum dynamical spin susceptibility, $\chi(\omega, \vec q)$. We find a strong violation of the Hertz-Millis form, contrary to all previous results. The form that we do observe provides strong evidence that the universal scaling is actually governed by the fixed point of Schlief, Lunts, and Lee [Phys. Rev. X 7, 021010 (2017)], even away from perfect hot-spot nesting. Our work provides concrete and novel predictions, via a controlled numerical calculation, for neutron scattering measurements of the spin susceptibility within the strange metal region of electron-doped cuprates and iron-based superconductors. Additionally, our results suggest that controlled analytical calculations of the critical theory near perfect hot-spot nesting can be used to make qualitatively correct predictions at larger nesting angles of all observables, including transport coefficients. Finally, the HMC method we introduce is generic and can be used to study other fermionic models of quantum criticality, where there is a strong need to simulate large systems.
