TI  - Topological Quantization of Superfluid Stiffness in Dirac Materials [arXiv]
LA  - eng
JF  - Arxiv
PY  - 2022
AB  - In this work, we put forward that Dirac materials are ideal candidates for observing the quantization of the superfluid stiffness. To show this, we re-formulate the theory of superfluid transport in terms of a response to gradients of the superconducting phase, and find that the superfluid stiffness is related to a synthetic Berry curvature. Our approach provides a transparent explanation for the puzzling prediction of quantized superfluid stiffness in short graphene Josephson junctions and superconducting bulk graphene. As we demonstrate, this quantization can be attributed to the realization of chiral anomaly, and we reveal that it remains robust upon adding nonuniform strain. Finally, we predict that signatures of chiral anomaly can be detected in the quantum capacitance of a Josephson junction consisting of a strained graphene hybrid and a conventional superconductor.
