TI  - Opening of bandgap in graphene: A complete overview to unexplored aspects
LA  - eng
JF  - Advances in Materials Science Research
VL  - 45
SP  - 151
EP  - 176
PY  - 2021
SN  - 1685070981, 1685071260, 9781685070984, 9781685071264
PB  - Nova Science Publishers, Inc.
AB  - Graphene is the present-day wonder material in electronics. The whole lot of perks offered by Graphene in terms of transport, electro-optical, mechanical, and thermo-elastic properties. Excellent mobility, field tunable carrier density, low electrical resistance, remarkable photo-transparency, good flexibility, unprecedented mechanical strength, high capacitive energy density, to name a few. Graphene exhibits the quantum Hall effect at room temperature. However, the single drawback of this otherwise brilliant material poses severe difficulties for Graphene to become the backbone of mainstream semiconductor devices in the near future. In Graphene, energy bands near Dirac point exhibit linear dispersion. Therefore, Graphene is regarded as a material with mass-less Fermions. That is Graphene has zero bandgap. In this context, it deserves mention that the opening of a considerable bandgap in Graphene, is quite challenging. Further, achieving such a desired bandgap without disturbing the transport properties of Graphene has remained an unachieved feat to date. This chapter offers a detailed account of all approaches that have been studied for opening the bandgap in Graphene. All the techniques that have been used to date, by both scientific and industrial communities, are covered. Also, a detailed review of theoretical predictions in this regard is presented. Also, experimental approaches that are currently used for opening the desired bandgap in Graphene are described. All possible pros and cons related to such practical techniques are also carefully highlighted. These include bandgap opening due to the impact of the underlying substrate, chemical substitution in the form of doping, etc. Advanced structures such as Graphene hybrids, Graphene-Nano-Ribbons (GNRs), patterned Graphene, typically folded Graphene, i.e., Graphene origami, etc., are discussed in detail. However, all these methods suffer from fabrication complexities. Besides, mobility degradation is an inherent outcome for all of such techniques, as mentioned earlier. Therefore, better approaches are necessary for successfully opening a suitable bandgap in Graphene. The following section of this chapter provides a comprehensive report on gap opening in Graphene-based on advanced concepts. It deserves mention that in Graphene, an intriguing interplay is exhibited between the electro-optical and thermo-elastic material properties and strain state of the material. Moreover, the magnetic state of Graphene exerts an evident yet complicated impact on the transport properties. Further, strain and spin are related in Graphene. Therefore, this chapter suggests advanced approaches based on combination of 'Straintronics' and 'Spintronics' for gap opening in Graphene. Finally, this chapter explores various aspects of Graphene-electronics. An exhaustive review of currently available technologies and potential ones has been provided. Excellent combination of strain- and spin-engineering are described here. That may result in the desired gap opening in Graphene without any significant derogation in its material properties. This in turn may enable large-scale, low-cost commercialization of this otherwise efficient material and therefore, elevate the semiconductor industry to new heights.
ER  -

