TI  - Comparing statistical predictions of quantum particle transit times in molecular systems to experimental measurements
LA  - eng
JF  - Journal of Theoretical and Computational Chemistry
VL  - 18
IS  - 8
PY  - 2019
SN  - 02196336, 17936888
PB  - World Scientific Publishing Co. Pte Ltd
DO  - 10.1142/S0219633619500391
AB  - The movement of quantum particles between distinct spatial regions is an essential feature of nanoscale devices. Consequently, theoretical methods for characterizing the transit time associated with this movement may aid in identifying and refining nanoscale systems with desirable transport properties. Herein, we explore the utility and range of validity of a recently reported probabilistic method for quantifying the timescale of quantum particle transit. The method is applied to intramolecular proton transfer in dicarbonyl compounds, and electron transfer in donor-bridge-acceptor molecules. Direct comparison is made between statistical predictions of proton and electron transfer times and corresponding transfer times deduced from the previously reported experimental observables. Insights provided by the method into the path of flow of probability density are discussed.
