AU  - Sun, Changqing
TI  - Spectrometric engineering for the secrecy of life and matter
LA  - chi
JF  - Kexue Tongbao/chinese Science Bulletin
VL  - 64
IS  - 26
SP  - 2667
EP  - 2671
PY  - 2019
SN  - 20959419, 0023074x
PB  - Chinese Academy of Sciences
DO  - 10.1360/TB-2019-0220
AB  - With the rapid advancement of synchrotron radiation apparatus and the popularity of electron and phonon spectroscopic instrument, fine and reliable analysis of the measured spectroscopic profiles for desired information becomes increasingly important. One could be able to control the processes of chemical reaction, structure transition, and electron and phonon transport as wishes only upon grasping with the controlling factors and mastering the essential information from the spectroscopic analysis, to fully fulfil the value of the costive instrument. Compared with the crystallography and surface morphology, the electron and phonon spectroscopic data are more complicated, but they provide much more profound information. For a given specimen, the curvature of the crystal potentials at equilibrium determines the phonon frequency while the equilibrium bond energy determines the energy level position shifting away from that of an isolated atom upon perturbation. A perturbation transits the crystal potential from its initial to a new equilibrium, causing bond relaxation that shifts both bond vibration frequency and electron bonding energies cooperatively. The shift may be positive or negative along the energy/frequency axis, subjecting to the type and extent of perturbation. A spectral peak features the Fourier transformation of electrons of the same binding energy or bonds of the same vibrating frequency, regardless of their locations, structure phases, or bond orientations, which allows focusing on one or more representatives for their same kinds in the entire specimen. One can determine the bond energy and electron distribution in the real and energy domains with high-resolution. A differential spectrometrics can distil the atomic scale, local, dynamic, perturbation- resolved and quantitative information on the bonding and electronic performance. Spectral data analysis is a subject of systematic engineering, which involves not only data acquisition, logic modelling, theoretical description, and numerical processing, but also interdisciplinary knowledge of physics, chemistry, mathematics, and life sciences. Spectrometrics of electron emission, diffraction, and multiple fields, liquid and solid phonon relaxation do reveal ever-unexpected quantitative information on the bonding, nonbonding, electronic and lattice dynamics pertaining to atomic irregular coordination at surface and interface, chemisorption, solvation, radiation, polarization, mechanical and thermal excitation. Systematic investigation shows that it is liable to shift the bond vibration frequencies and electronic binding energies by perturbing the crystal potentials in the Hamiltonian of quantum approaches through applying mechanical, electrical, magnetic, thermal and coordination fields. One can derive information regarding bond and electron energy relaxation from the electronic energy and phonon frequency spectral shift with further computations. Such information provides guidelines for prediction and modification materials performance. For instance, one can understand the atomistic catalytic ability of the accepter-type Rh and the donor-like Pt catalyst from the energy shift due to atomic undercoordination. One can also learn the mechanism of generation, coupling, frequency tuning and transport of THz signal by stimulating O:H bond vibration, to mediate the processes of living species. Lagrangian-Laplacian transition of the measured segmental hydrogen bond (O:H-O) length and energy into their force constant and bond energy has led to the potential paths for the relaxed O:H-O bond under perturbation, which not only resolves multiple mysteries of water ice but also provides strategies for engineering aqueous solutions as one wishes.
