AB  - The Rossio tunnel was built in 1890 and connects the Campolide Station in the north of Lisbon with the Rossio Station in the urban city centre of Lisbon, with connections to the Metro network. Due to structural problems which appeared during the construction phase in 1988, the tunnel was put under constant monitoring. For safety reasons the railway line was taken out of operation in October 2004 and because of its great strategic importance the track was rebuilt following completion of the necessary structural works. The Portuguese National Railway Network (REFER) selected a continuously supported fastenerless embedded rail system (CSFERS) from CDM range of track solutions: the CDM-QTrack system. There was demand for a high level of vibration isolation; for the "-10 dBV" zones a soft CSFERS was chosen (CDM-QT-XP, eXtra high Performance), whereas for the more sensitive areas a classic CSFERS (CDM-QT-HP, High Performance) system was installed in a floating slab track, using resilient mats from the CDM range to obtain a minimum isolation of 20 dBV. A measurement campaign was done, in which the vibration levels, rail deflections and rail roughness after 7, 70 and 700 days were measured. The installed systems have been tested extensively in comparison with discrete supported rail and results show that the CDM-QT-XP system delivers extremely good vibration isolation performance whilst also delivering a far lower rate of corrugation than discrete supported rail. This paper describes the installed solutions in Rossio tunnel, the vibration measurements taken and presents the results. The Portugese national permanent way owner (REFER) was confident that a CSFERS system in CDM-QT-XP version would deliver excellent vibration isolation performance, even in areas without a floating slab, with the added advantages of fast installation and a multimodal platform inside the tunnel for easy evacuation and maintenance operations.
