AB  - It is widely believed that compost produces lower greenhouse emissions than landfill. Government policies in many countries encourage diversion of organics to compost. Australia, like the European Union, plans to progressively reduce organic waste in landfill. This study aims to test whether this policy in fact reduces greenhouse emissions. The IPCC Guidelines for National Greenhouse Gas Inventories (2006) were used to compare total greenhouse emissions from landfill, composting and incineration of organic municipal waste. Default values for a dry temperate Mediterranean climate (as in southern Australia, Greece, Spain, Portugal and Italy) were used to calculate landfill emissions. It was assumed that approximately 75% of landfill emissions are captured: detailed monitoring of a landfill site in Melbourne, Australia, supports this assumption.
