AB  - The incorporation of nanoparticles into desalination and water treatment membranes is considered as one of the most promising step toward resolving two of the most important challenges of membranes: the selectivity-permeability trade-off and the pervasive problem of fouling. In addition, significant improvement in other desirable properties such as mechanical and thermal resistance is also envisaged. The anticipated nanoparticle enhancement of membrane performance derives from nanoparticles' unique quantum and surface characteristics that are not manifested in the bulk material. The most important nanoparticles for the development of next generation high flux, high selectivity membranes are carbon nanotubes, aquaporin membrane proteins, and nanozeolite crystals due to their molecular-size channel for phenomenal superfast transport of water and solute rejection. However, the scale-up of these nanomaterials to macro-dimension required for membrane application has proven to be very challenging despite extensive research. The application of thin film composite polymeric membrane has allowed some of the unique properties of these nanoparticles to be harnessed for membrane desalination and water treatment but the achievement is still orders of magnitude below theoretical predictions. Perhaps, the most promising material for the resolution of the fouling problem is nanotitania with the potential of self-cleaning, foulant degradation, antimicrobial effect, and wettability modification upon electromagnetic irradiation. However, critical improvement in photocatalysis and more effective utilization of visible light are necessary to bring these unique properties to bear. Other important membrane-relevant nanoparticles are nanosilver, nanosilica, and nanoalumina. This chapter overviews the challenges, properties, and prospects of these novel nanoparticles that together constitute a most exciting field of fundamental and practical research for innovation toward water sustainability.
